metadata.name: BRUTALIST MOVEMENT #9
metadata.description:
Inspired and fascinated by Brutalism, Modernism and Bauhaus, I've started to explore the deeper connections of architecture using pixel art in a clean, minimalistic and unique way.

The BRUTALIST MOVEMENT project represents the next step in this process. It's an animated generative experiment that focuses on finding the simplest and fewest components that - when generated randomly - always create structures resembling buildings: from small modern houses through industrial facilities to gigantic brutalist monuments.

This resulted in 4 main components: Base, Extension, Gap and Window. These entities are used randomly to create Blocks that form the final structure. 
The whole process is also strictly accompanied by 4 distinct components to hold colors and to be set by randomly chosen palettes: Sky, Sun, Shadow, Window.

Features consist of a mixture of the above components.

The project is animated to show how the buildings come to life. It's also a nice way to show what's going on in the background, because from time to time a bigger block would surely hide interesting smaller ones :) 

Press these keys:
's' - to download a larger resolution PNG
'n' - to shuffle through the 'depth' of Blocks, aka placing them from front to back and vice versa. This is a nice feature to show structures hidden by others and also a cool way to create iterations inside the iteration - sub-iterations - we can say :)
'r' - to reset the Blocks' depths to default

Please note:
Everything you see is generated, animated and drawn real-time. No layered transparent PNGs, PFP or similar!

Have fun and inspiration!


@cloudnoise © 2022

☁︎

Created with P5.js library.

metadata.name: Ichigo #327
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (苺/ いちご), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Kinetograms #353
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.

🄷🄰-0

Happy Accidents #0 

Simple, colourful, playful, happy.

These 101 tokens will act as the Happy Accidents reserve list for future releases.

Thanks for collecting! 
Click the image or press ‘s’ or ‘S’ in live mode to download png.

metadata.name: Stepping Stones #269
metadata.description:
"Stepping Stones" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022

Stepping Stones explores the idea that the whole is greater than the sum of its parts. Simple patterns, shapes, textures, and colors are arranged in randomly selected ways. Overlaying shapes distort and blend, breaking these objects apart and causing complex forms to emerge. Combining these individual features together results in varying outcomes, from surprisingly simple to wildly chaotic.

---------------

Controls:
Press 1-6 to change the scale of the canvas (1 = default, 2500px x 2500px, 6 = 15,000px x 15,000px)
S (or double tap on mobile): Save output at current size
C: Toggle cutout shapes visibility
H: Toggle cutout outlines visibility
B: Iterate border sizes (none, default, 1.5x, 2x, 3x)
T: Toggle texture visibility
F: Toggle fullscreen
Add the url params x and y to set custom dimensions. For example, add &x=1500&y=500 for a 1500px x 500px image

---------------

Tyler Boswell (@teaboswell) 2022

metadata.name: Udnē #302
metadata.description:
Udnē is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022.

Udnē is a collection of asymmetric textural compositions. It's a search for creating harmonies and disharmonies by combining 3 colors with 3 unsynchronized mathematical equations. Udnē explores the beauty within triadic compositions while attempting to integrate two contrasting textures by forming instances of non-figurative scenes. The collection is a reflection of integrated and contrasting textures in micro and macro scale that we see in our everyday life environment.

You can press 's' in liveMode to save as 1000x1000px .png.

In liveMode, add '&density=7’ to the end of the URL to render at high resolution (7000x7000px). You can use 5, 7 or 10 for different resolutions. It will automatically download when the rendering is finished. 

Some compositions might take longer to render in low-performance computers. Please be patient and enjoy the process!

As a rare probability there is an intentionally kept glitch.

Made with p5js.
@distcollective, November 2022

metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #4348
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

Access List reserves were given to holders of the following PFP collections created by culla
2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

share your tokens on social media with #genxyznft
Made with love by culla using p5.js

metadata.name: SPOT #61
metadata.description:
A study of circles, sizes, lines, colors, grains and alphas. The composition consists solely of 2d shapes but generates a 3d look. The base colors use a random chromaticity factor which results in a wild range of combinations. There is a 70% change on a dark background and 30% on a light background also 15% change on black and white. 

Press s in live mode for a 2000x2800 download

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje December 2022

metadata.name: Textura #55
metadata.description:
"Textura"

My initial goal was to create artwork that could trigger raw, visceral emotions and feelings. A polar opposite to the polite, clinical precision of some other collections, I wanted to embrace the grittier side of abstract art. 

This turned out to be a rather difficult project for me. It was a departure from my usual figurative / ink line style, where most of the time I find it straightforward to tell a "good" output from a "bad" one. Here, out of my comfort zone, I couldn't tell. I liked some outputs, I hated some. The ones I hated, usually would be someone else's favorites. Abstract art is hard !

After a while, some patterns started to emerge. The overall feedback was that, generally:
- blue outputs were peaceful
- orange ones were intense and aggressive
- black and white ones were oppressive and sometimes disturbing

If you can associate an emotion to any given output, I feel like I will have achieved my goal. Thank you to everyone who provided feedback !

 
Technically, this project also posed a number of challenges:
- how to blend a large number of procedural textures in a smooth, yet natural way
- how to make sure the final piece has some kind of depth, visible beyond the intricate layering
- how to optimize contrast and get vibrant results

This was mostly achieved by spending a lot of time designing and fine-tuning color schemes - enhanced versions of color palettes, that also contain pre and post-processing settings.

The collection features a total of 31 color schemes. 

Key commands:
'1', '2', '4': increase resolution
's': save png
'n': toggle background noise
'c': toggle background canvas texture

On mobile devices, the rendering resolution is reduced to deal with memory limitations.

metadata.name: d/e/m/boss invaders #175
metadata.description:
Invaders is an algorithm that builds rows of rectangles and plays with repetition, colors and depth order.
Outputs reminds me space invaders, but some looks like motherboard circuits, temples, or just a overhead map from a hotel room emergency exit

Please be patient, it takes a while to render (25-45 secs) and draws around 6M circles during 4 steps.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

Invaders is part of a series playing with textures creating emboss/deboss effect.

de/
 /boss
em/

100% code, made with p5js
See License.md
